98–1263","1220–Male":"1220–Overleden","1224–1270":"1224–1270","1155–1240":"1155–1240","1183–1263":"1183–1263","1205":"1205","1224":"1224","1223":"1223","1155":"1155","1220":"1220","1198":"1198","1263":"1263","1240":"1240","3 October 1263":"3 oktober 1263","1183":"1183","1270":"1270","Renfrewshire, Scotland":"Renfrewshire, Schotland","Cunninghame, Ayrshire, Scotland":"Cunningham, Ayrshire, Schotland","Kilmarnock, Ayrshire, Scotland":"Kilmarnock, Ayrshire, Schotland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Scotland":"Schotland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1205–3 October 1263":"1205–3 October 1263","1205–1263":"1205–1263","1198–1263":"1198–1263","1220–Male":"1220–Deceased","1224–1270":"1224–1270","1155–1240":"1155–1240","1183–1263":"1183–1263","1205":"1205","1224":"1224","1223":"1223","1155":"1155","1220":"1220","1198":"1198","1263":"1263","1240":"1240","3 October 1263":"3 October 1263","1183":"1183","1270":"1270","Renfrewshire, Scotland":"Renfrewshire, Scotland","Cunninghame, Ayrshire, Scotland":"Cunningham, Ayrshire, Scotland","Kilmarnock, Ayrshire, Scotland":"Kilmarnock, Ayrshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","Scotland":"Scotland, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Boyd","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish: habitational name from the island of Bute in the Firth of Clyde, from <i>Bòid</i> (genitive case of <i>Bòd</i>, the Gaelic name of the island of Bute) or <i>Bòideach</i>, denoting a person from Bute. Alternatively, the name may denote descendants of a <i>Gilla filius Boed</i>, who appears in reference to Glasgow Cathedral in the early 12th century, perhaps from the Gaelic personal name <i>Boite</i>, of uncertain origin.","Scottish and Irish: from the Gaelic epithet <i>buidhe</i> ‘yellow(-haired)’. Compare   Bowie  .","Manx: from <b>Mac Gille Buidhe</b> ‘son of the yellow-haired lad’ (compare 2 above)."],"variants":[{"name":"Bowie","meanings":["Scottish: from Gaelic <i>buidhe</i> ‘yellow’, i.e. ‘yellow-haired’, pronounced as two syllables. The equivalent term in Ireland is <i>buí</i>, often Anglicized as <i>boy</i>. The surname may also be a shortened form of   Gilboy  .","Irish: Anglicized form of <b>Ó Buadhaigh</b> (see   Bogue  )."]},{"name":"Boyde","meanings":["Scottish (Glasgow): variant of   Boyd  ."]}]},{"name":"ll","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: variant of <b>Alle</b>, perhaps from an unrecorded Middle English personal name <i>Alle</i>, which may be a variant of Middle English <i>Ale</i> and <i>Ally</i> (see   Alley  ). Alternatively, post-medieval examples may be a variant of   Hall  ,   Halle  , with loss of initial <i>H-</i>.","Probably also an Americanized form of German   Ahl   or   Al  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Alley","meanings":["English: from the Middle English personal name <i>Ally</i>, <i>Alli</i>, as forms such as <i>Johannes filius Alli</i> (Norfolk, 1205) make clear. It may be a pet form of   Alexander  ,   Alan  ,   Alice  , or   Alison  , or a survival of Old Danish <i>Alli</i>, Old Swedish <i>Alle</i>, found as <i>Alli</i> in the Domesday Book.","In some cases also an altered form of French <b>Hallé</b> (see   Halle   2) or of some other similar (like-sounding) surname.","Variant of   Allee   2, a surname of French origin."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Dictus","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Gerhard, Fritz, Kurt, Otto, Reinhold.","German: from a vernacular short form of the Latin personal name <i>Benedictus</i> (see   Bennett  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Bennett","meanings":["The normal medieval vernacular form of   Benedict  , borne by women as well as men in the past. Now sometimes used as an antiquarian revival, but more often a transferred use of the surname derived from the medieval given name."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir Robert Dictus Boyd  ll 1st Laird of Kilmarnock was born in 1205, in Kilmarnock, Ayrshire, Scotland, United Kingdom, his father, Sir Robert Boidh de Boyd, was 50 and his mother, Lady A FitzAlan, was 22. He had at least 2 sons with Avellina Fitz Alan Mac Gilbert. He died on 3 October 1263, in Cunningham, Ayrshire, Scotland, at the age of 58."},"et":{"1205–3 October 1263":"1205–3. oktoober 1263","1205–1263":"1205–1263","1198–1263":"1198–1263","1220–Male":"1220–Surnud","1224–1270":"1224–1270","1155–1240":"1155–1240","1183–1263":"1183–1263","1205":"1205","1224":"1224","1223":"1223","1155":"1155","1220":"1220","1198":"1198","1263":"1263","1240":"1240","3 October 1263":"3. oktoober 1263","1183":"1183","1270":"1270","Renfrewshire, Scotland":"Renfrewshire, Scotland","Cunninghame, Ayrshire, Scotland":"Cunningham, Ayrshire, Scotland","Kilmarnock, Ayrshire, Scotland":"Kilmarnock, Ayrshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Scotland":"Šotimaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1205–3 October 1263":"1205–3. lokakuuta 1263","1205–1263":"1205–126